    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1978-08-14T03:49:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1978-08-14T03:49:00-05:00" n="139"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d139">
                <head>139. Telegram From the Embassy in the Soviet Union to the Department of
                        State<note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d139fn1">Source: Department of State,
                        Office of the Secretariat Staff, Special Adviser to the Secretary (<gloss
                            target="#t_SMS_1">S/MS</gloss>) on Soviet Affairs <persName
                            corresp="#p_SHM_1">Marshall Shulman</persName>—Jan 21, 77–Jan 19, 81,
                        Lot 81D109, Box 3, CV–<persName corresp="#p_GAA_1">Gromyko</persName> Letter
                        (Camp David) 8/11/78. Secret; Cherokee; Immediate; <gloss
                            target="#t_NODIS_1">Nodis</gloss>.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Moscow</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1978-08-14T08:49:00+00:00">August 14, 1978, 0849Z</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>19273. For the Secretary from the Ambassador. Subject: Message to <persName
                        corresp="#p_GAA_1">Gromyko</persName>. Ref: State 203927.<note n="2"
                        xml:id="d139fn2">See <ref target="#d138">Document 138</ref>.</note>
                </p>
                <pb facs="0476" n="441" xml:id="pg_441"/>
                <p>1. In absence of <persName corresp="#p_GAA_1">Gromyko</persName>, who is
                    vacationing outside of Moscow, I delivered your letter to Acting Foreign
                    Minister <persName corresp="#p_KGM_1">Korniyenko</persName> morning of August
                    14.</p>
                <p>2. After reading the letter, and undertaking to transmit it to <persName
                        corresp="#p_GAA_1">Gromyko</persName>, <persName corresp="#p_KGM_1"
                        >Korniyenko</persName> commented that your hope that the Soviet Union would
                    support the Camp David summit meeting was unfounded. The Soviet side considers
                    the path of Egypt-Israeli talks to be a blind alley which can cause “dangerous
                    complications” in the Middle East. Noting that in my view the Soviet position
                    was wrong, I told <persName corresp="#p_KGM_1">Korniyenko</persName> that as a
                    careful reader of the Soviet press I was not surprised at his response.</p>
                <p>3. Regarding a possible <persName corresp="#p_WAP_1">Warnke</persName> visit to
                    the Soviet Union, I asked <persName corresp="#p_KGM_1">Korniyenko</persName> if
                    he could clarify <persName corresp="#p_GAA_1">Gromyko</persName>’s vacation
                    plans. <persName corresp="#p_KGM_1">Korniyenko</persName> replied that <persName
                        corresp="#p_GAA_1">Gromyko</persName> was presently on vacation outside of
                    the capital. He said the Soviet side would not want <persName corresp="#p_WAP_1"
                        >Warnke</persName> to postpone his trip, however. <persName
                        corresp="#p_KGM_1">Korniyenko</persName> himself would go on vacation
                    shortly (tomorrow in fact, but only for 10 days) in Moscow and therefore he
                    would be available to meet <persName corresp="#p_WAP_1">Warnke</persName> at any
                    time. In response to my hypothetical question, <persName corresp="#p_KGM_1"
                        >Korniyenko</persName> indicated that it might be possible for <persName
                        corresp="#p_WAP_1">Warnke</persName> to meet with <persName
                        corresp="#p_GAA_1">Gromyko</persName> outside of Moscow, although <persName
                        corresp="#p_KGM_1">Korniyenko</persName> would of course have to discuss
                    this with <persName corresp="#p_GAA_1">Gromyko</persName> should <persName
                        corresp="#p_WAP_1">Warnke</persName> wish to arrange such a meeting.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_TOM_1">
                            <hi rend="strong">Toon</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
